President Biden delivered a speech in the East Room of the White House, commemorating the 40th anniversary of the HIV/AIDS epidemic. He thanked individuals and organizations for their tireless work in fighting HIV/AIDS and acknowledged the progress that has been made in reducing new HIV transmissions and improving care for individuals living with HIV. He also recognized the need to address racial and gender disparities in healthcare and called for the elimination of HIV criminalization laws. President Biden emphasized the importance of global efforts in fighting HIV/AIDS, including the role of the President's Emergency Plan for AIDS Relief (PEPFAR) and the Global Fund. He expressed optimism that with continued dedication, HIV transmission can be eliminated and the epidemic can be brought under control both in the United States and around the world.